DataFeature.Name: AWG Number
DataFeature.Definition: The American Wire Gauge (AWG) number of the conductor in the power line.
DataFeature.SourceDescription: This data feature is extracted from the AWG number section of the input text.

EvaluatedAnnotations.Name: nominal diameter of the auxiliary conductor (AWG)
EvaluatedAnnotations.Definition: size of the nominal cross section surface of auxiliary conductor indicated by the American Wire Gauge System. American Wire Gauge, abbreviated AWG, is a coding for wire diameters and is mainly used in North America. It identifies electrical lines made of stranded wire and solid wire and is mainly used in electrical engineering to describe the cross-section of wires
EvaluatedAnnotations.Reason: Not relevant as it refers to the auxiliary conductor, not the main conductor.

EvaluatedAnnotations.Name: AWG size of main conductors
EvaluatedAnnotations.Definition: size of the cross section surface of main conductor indicated by the American Wire Gauge System. American Wire Gauge, abbreviated AWG, is a coding for wire diameters and is mainly used in North America. It identifies electrical lines made of stranded wire and solid wire and is mainly used in electrical engineering to describe the cross-section of wires
EvaluatedAnnotations.Reason: Not relevant as it refers to the main conductors, not the specific AWG number of the conductor in the power line.

EvaluatedAnnotations.Name: min. AWG number
EvaluatedAnnotations.Definition: minimum value of the AWG area. This is an electrical engineering term
EvaluatedAnnotations.Reason: Not relevant as it refers to the minimum value of the AWG area, not the specific AWG number of the conductor in the power line.
